Here's a C++ program that reads a text file line by line, counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file, and outputs the result:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <vector>

int countOccurrences(const std::string& word, const std::string& filename) {
    std::ifstream file(filename);
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file: " << filename << std::endl;
        return -1;
    }

    std::unordered_map<std::string, int> wordCount;
    int count = 0;

    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        std::string wordToCount = line.substr(word.size() - 1);
        if (wordToCount == word) {
            wordCount[word]++;
            count++;
        }
    }

    file.close();

    return count;
}

int main() {
    std::string wordToCount = "example";
    std::string filename = "input.txt";

    int occurrences = countOccurrences(wordToCount, filename);
    if (occurrences == -1) {
        std::cerr << "Error counting occurrences: " << filename << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    std::cout << "Occurrences of '" << wordToCount << "' in file: " << occurrences << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we first include the necessary header files: `iostream`, `fstream`, `string`, `unordered_map`, and `vector`. We then define the `countOccurrences` function, which takes two arguments: `wordToCount`, which is the word we want to count occurrences of, and `filename`, which is the name of the input file.

Inside the function, we first open the input file using `std::ifstream`. If the file is not open, we output an error message and return -1.

Next, we create an `unordered_map` called `wordCount` to store the count of occurrences of each word. We initialize a variable `count` to 0 to keep track of the number of occurrences.

We then read each line of the file using `std::getline` and extract the word to count using `line.substr(word.size() - 1)`. If the extracted word matches the `wordToCount` variable, we increment its count in the `wordCount` map and increment the `count` variable.

After reading all the lines in the file, we close the file using `file.close()`.

Finally, we return the `count` variable, which represents the number of occurrences of the `wordToCount` word in the input file.

In the `main` function, we define the `wordToCount` variable and the `filename` variable, which are the words we want to count occurrences of and the name of the input file, respectively.

We call the `countOccurrences` function with `wordToCount` and `filename` as arguments, and store the result in the `occurrences` variable. If the function returns -1, we output an error message and return 1. Otherwise, we output the number of occurrences of the `wordToCount` word in the input file using `std::cout`.

Note that this program assumes that the input file contains only one line per line, with the word to count at the end of the line. If the input file contains multiple lines with the same word, the program will only count the first occurrence. If you want to count occurrences of the word across multiple lines, you can modify the `countOccurrences` function to read the entire file into a string and then split it into lines using `std::getline` and `std::istringstream`.
